<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-10-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-10-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="399" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d399">
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                    <head>No. 394.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Porter</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Curry</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-10-04"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 4,
                            1886</date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>Mr. Porter asks whether an early date for a definite answer can be named. He
                        states that if the President is compelled to delay his action such
                        inconvenience and loss will be caused that the postponement can not be long
                        continued.</p>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>